Ques: Difference between Service and deployment in Kubernetes ?
Ans: “A Deployment in Kubernetes is responsible for managing pod lifecycle, scaling, rolling updates, and maintaining the desired number of replicas. A Service is responsible for providing stable networking and 
load balancing access to pods. Deployments manage application instances, while Services expose and route traffic to those instances.”

“No, a pod is not limited to a single Kubernetes Service. Multiple Services can target the same pod using different label selectors or expose different ports and use cases. Services in Kubernetes are loosely coupled
networking abstractions that select pods dynamically through labels rather than having a one-to-one relationship.”

A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes and represents one or more tightly coupled containers running together on the same node. Containers inside a pod share networking, storage, and lifecycle. 
Pods are ephemeral and are usually managed by higher-level controllers like Deployments or StatefulSets.

Pods in Kubernetes are ephemeral, meaning they are temporary and can be created, destroyed, or replaced at any time. When a pod fails or is terminated, Kubernetes does not repair it but creates a new replacement 
pod. This is why applications should not depend on pod identity, IP, or local storage, and instead use services and persistent storage for stability.
